explanation: For each function symbol: - OS_ObjectIdGetById: The target calls this directly; its implementation must be inspected to see if it invokes any <string.h> functions (memcpy/strncpy/etc.) or otherwise manipulates buffers derived from IDs/tokens. - OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, OS_ObjectIdConvertToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: These are the internal callees of OS_ObjectIdGetById (per the static call graph). Their source is required because any use of string handling functions or array indexing that could access out-of-bounds memory may occur inside them. - OS_CondVarSignal_Impl: The target calls this if OS_ObjectIdGetById succeeds; its implementation must be examined for any string functions or buffer accesses. - OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: This is called by OS_CondVarSignal_Impl; its implementation may perform indexing or token-to-pointer conversions that could lead to out-of-bounds accesses or call string functions. For each type/macro/global: - OS_object_token_t: Definition is required to know the contents (fields, sizes, index/value encodings) used for subsequent indexing or pointer derivation; this affects bounds reasoning. - osal_id_t: Type definition is needed to understand value ranges passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById. - int32: Needed to interpret return codes and any arithmetic that might affect control flow (e.g., error paths that skip checks). - OS_SUCCESS, OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_CONDVAR: Macro/constant definitions are needed to understand which code paths are taken (successful lookup vs error) and the object-type checks that may influence which buffers/arrays are accessed. - OS_global_object_table: Any object table or global structure referenced by the object-id conversion/indexing functions must be inspected to determine actual buffer sizes and indexing bounds; the exact name may vary, but the global object arrays/tables used by the above functions are required to judge whether string functions operate within bounds. Together these symbols let the next analyst inspect all code paths and data layouts that could call or be affected by <string.h> functions and therefore determine MISRA C compliance with respect to out-of-bounds accesses.
